ct to very little regulation. Applying the Fourth Amendment’s prohibition on unreasonable searches and seizures, Slobogin argues that courts should prod legislatures into enacting more meaningful protection against government overreaching. In setting forth a comprehensive framework meant to preserve rights guaranteed by the Constitution without compromising the government’s ability to investigate criminal acts, Slobogin offers a balanced regulatory regime that should intrigue everyone concerned about privacy rights in the digital age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  agovernment, politics, political, academic, scholarly, amendments, constitution, constitutional, consent, monitoring, daily life, tv, electronics, closed circuit, cctv, technology, financial, information, privacy, email, phone, medical, personal, history, search, seizure, rights, legislature, overreach, criminal, digital, contemporary, modern, present day, law, united states, usa, america.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226762944423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226762944/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles